### B. Dictionary values

The docs show that `values(d)` returns an iterator over dictionary values, and `collect(values(d))` turns them into an array. ([docs.julialang.org][1])

```julia
d = Dict("a" => 1, "b" => 2)
println(collect(values(d)))
```

### C. Array math

Julia supports element-wise array math with broadcasting syntax, which is central to numerical work. ([docs.julialang.org][4])

```julia
numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
println(numbers .* 10)
```

